Background

This report provides a brief summary of the weekly ensemble forecast from the COVID-19 Forecast Hub based on forecasts submitted on February 27, 2023. In collaboration with the US CDC, our team aggregates COVID-19 forecasts from dozens of teams around the globe. Typically on Wednesday of each week, a summary of the week's forecasts from the COVID-19 Forecast Hub appear on the official CDC COVID-19 forecasting page.

Every week, teams submit their forecasts to the COVID-19 Forecast Hub. This past week, 25 models were submitted.

Each Tuesday, we combine the most recent forecasts from each team into a single "ensemble" forecast of reported COVID-19 deaths and hospitalizations at the state and national level. As of February 20, 2023, we are no longer working with case forecasts, but older reports include case forecast evaluations. At the moment, we only generate ensemble forecasts for up to four weeks into the future, as the available evidence suggests that models are less accurate at longer forecast horizons.

An archive of weekly reports from the COVID-19 Forecast Hub can be found at this page.

COVID-19 Forecasts

National level

This week, our ensemble combined forecasts from 20 different models.

At the national level, the ensemble model predicts that weekly totals of observed deaths in each of the next four weeks will be between 2,200 and 2,300 deaths with around 1,128,700 deaths by March 25, 2023 (95% prediction interval: 1,125,190 - 1,132,148).

For the week ending March 25, 2023, the ensemble forecasts that reported COVID-19 deaths in the US will be between 700 and 4,200 (95% prediction interval: 710 - 4,235).

As of September 28, 2021 the ensemble forecast only reports 14 day ahead forecasts for hospitalizations, due to persistent large inaccuracies observed when forecasting beyond that.

For March 13, 2023 COVID-19 daily hospitalizations in the US will be between 1,800 and 6,100 (95% prediction interval: 1,761 - 6,090).

You can explore the full set of models, including their forecasts for past weeks online at the Forecast Hub interactive visualization.
